Project Overview

This analysis uses General Social Survey (GSS) data to examine how cognitive ability affects income across different education levels. The GSS includes a vocabulary test (wordsum) that serves as a proxy for academic ability, allowing us to estimate âability biasââthe extent to which observed education premiums reflect underlying cognitive differences rather than purely educational effects.

This analysis has obvious limitations: we cannot cleanly separate ability from education, lack data on fields of study or institutional quality, and assume wordsum adequately captures cognitive ability, etc. We also make simplifying assumptions about GSS survey design.

We use specific ability percentile cutoffs (24th, 41st, 73rd, 82nd) that correspond to college completion rates from Bryan Caplanâs research. This allows results to feed into financial models calculating the return on college investment for students of different ability levels.

Data & Methodology

The analysis uses GSS data from 2016â2022, focusing on workforce participants. The wordsum variable (vocabulary test score) serves as a proxy for cognitive ability, while income16 provides family income data in ranges that we convert to numeric midpoints. We inflation-adjust to 2022 dollars.

Load and Filter GSS Data

# Load GSS data

data(gss_all)

# Filter for workforce participants with complete data
gss1a <- gss_all %>%
  select(year, wordsum, age, educ, degree, rincome, income16, wrkstat, wtssps) %>%
  filter(year >= 2016,
                wrkstat %in% c(1, 2, 3, 4),  # In workforce
                !is.na(wordsum), !is.na(income16),
                educ >= 0, degree >= 0)

# Convert wordsum to percentiles (unweighted)

gss1a <- gss1a %>%
  mutate(wordsum_percentile = percent_rank(wordsum) * 100)

Income Range Conversion

# Map income16 categories to numeric midpoints (see GSS variable docs)

get_midpoint <- function(x) {
  if (is.na(x) || is.null(x)) return(NA_real_)
  x <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(as.character(x)))
  if (is.na(x)) return(NA_real_)
  if (x %in% c(-100, -98, -97, -90)) return(NA_real_)  # NA / DK / SKIP / REFUSED
  if (x == 1)  return(500)     # UNDER $1,000
  if (x == 26) return(185000)  # $170,000 OR OVER (chosen anchor)
  if (x >= 2 && x <= 25) {
    range <- switch(as.character(x),
      "2"=c(1000,2999),   "3"=c(3000,3999),   "4"=c(4000,4999),   "5"=c(5000,5999),
      "6"=c(6000,6999),   "7"=c(7000,7999),   "8"=c(8000,9999),   "9"=c(10000,12499),
      "10"=c(12500,14999),"11"=c(15000,17499),"12"=c(17500,19999),"13"=c(20000,22499),
      "14"=c(22500,24999),"15"=c(25000,29999),"16"=c(30000,34999),"17"=c(35000,39999),
      "18"=c(40000,49999),"19"=c(50000,59999),"20"=c(60000,74999),"21"=c(75000,89999),
      "22"=c(90000,109999),"23"=c(110000,129999),"24"=c(130000,149999),"25"=c(150000,169999)
    )
    return(mean(range))
  }
  NA_real_
}

gss1a$income16_numeric <- vapply(gss1a$income16, get_midpoint, numeric(1))

Inflation Adjustment

# Adjust to 2022 dollars, using BLS CPIAUCSL

inflation_lookup <- tibble(
  year = c(2016, 2018, 2021, 2022),
  cpi  = c(81.2,  84.6,  94.0, 100.0)
)

gss1a <- gss1a %>%
  left_join(inflation_lookup, by = "year") %>%
  mutate(income16_numeric_22 = income16_numeric / cpi * 100)

Education Categories

# Parsing gss variables

combine_education <- function(educ, degree) {
  case_when(
    educ %in% c(-99, -98, -97) | degree %in% c(-99, -98, -97) ~ NA_character_,
    educ < 12 ~ "Less than High School",
    educ == 12 & degree == 1 ~ "High School Graduate",
    educ > 12 & degree == 1 ~ "Some College (No Degree)",
    degree == 2 ~ "Associate/Junior College",
    degree == 3 ~ "Bachelor's",
    degree == 4 ~ "Graduate Degree",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  )
}

gss1a_clean <- gss1a %>%
  mutate(
    edu_combined = combine_education(educ, degree),
    income16_numeric = as.numeric(income16_numeric),
    wordsum_percentile = as.numeric(wordsum_percentile),
    age = as.numeric(age)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(edu_combined))

# Show weighted sample sizes by education
gss1a_clean %>%
  count(edu_combined, wt = wtssps) %>%
  arrange(desc(n), digits = 0,
               format.args = list(big.mark = ","))

Analysis Results

Regression Model

# Basic regression model

model <- stats::lm(
  income16_numeric_22 ~ wordsum_percentile * edu_combined + age + I(age^2),
  data = gss1a_clean,
  weights = wtssps
)
summary(model)

Predicted Income by Ability and Education

# Predictions at selected percentiles and age 42 (age of median US worker)

inference <- expand.grid(
  wordsum_percentile = c(25, 50, 75),
  edu_combined = c("High School Graduate", "Some College (No Degree)", "Bachelor's"),
  age = 42
)

inference$predicted_income <- as.numeric(predict(model, newdata = inference))

predicted_values <- inference %>% 
  select(-age) %>% 
  mutate(predicted_income = dollar(predicted_income)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = wordsum_percentile,
    values_from = predicted_income,
    names_prefix = "Ability_"
  ) %>% 
  rename(
    `Education Level` = edu_combined,
    `25th Percentile` = Ability_25,
    `50th Percentile` = Ability_50,
    `75th Percentile` = Ability_75
  )

print(predicted_values)

Key Findings Visualization

# Wordsum is still correlated with earnings, even controlling for education. 
# Interestingly, the slope is highest for people with some college,
# but no degree.

chart_data <- gss1a_clean %>%
  filter(edu_combined %in% c("High School Graduate", "Some College (No Degree)", "Bachelor's")) %>%
  group_by(edu_combined, wordsum_percentile) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_income  = stats::weighted.mean(income16_numeric_22, wtssps, na.rm = TRUE),
    total_weight = sum(wtssps, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    edu_combined = factor(edu_combined,
      levels = c("High School Graduate", "Some College (No Degree)", "Bachelor's")),
    wordsum_percentile = as.numeric(wordsum_percentile)
  ) %>%
  drop_na(mean_income, total_weight, wordsum_percentile)

ggplot(chart_data, aes(x = wordsum_percentile, y = mean_income)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = total_weight), alpha = 0.6, color = "steelblue", na.rm = TRUE) +
  facet_wrap(~edu_combined) +
  stat_smooth(
    aes(weight = total_weight, group = 1),
    method = "lm", formula = y ~ x, se = TRUE, color = "darkred"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format(), breaks = seq(0, 150000, by = 25000)) +
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(1, 4), guide = "none") +
  labs(
    title = "Family Income vs. Cognitive Ability by Education Level",
    subtitle = "GSS Data 2016â2022 | Bubble size represents survey-weighted sample size",
    x = "Cognitive Ability (Wordsum Percentile)",
    y = "Mean Family Income (2022 dollars)",
    caption = "Source: General Social Survey"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    strip.text = element_text(size = 11, face = "bold"),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10)
  )

Income Premiums by Ability Level

# Computes predicted incomes across ability percentiles and education levels, 
# then calculates ratios relative to median ability (50th percentile).

# Broader grid to compute ratios
inference_all <- expand.grid(
  wordsum_percentile = c(24, 41, 50, 73, 82),
  edu_combined = unique(gss1a_clean$edu_combined),
  age = 42
)

inference_all$predicted_values <- as.numeric(predict(model, newdata = inference_all))

inference_50 <- filter(inference_all, wordsum_percentile == 50)

df_ratio <- inference_all %>%
  left_join(inference_50, by = "edu_combined", suffix = c("", "_50")) %>%
  mutate(ratio = predicted_values / predicted_values_50)

ratio_export <- df_ratio %>%
  filter(edu_combined %in% c("High School Graduate", "Some College (No Degree)", "Bachelor's")) %>%
  select(wordsum_percentile, edu_combined, predicted_values, ratio)

# Show nicely
ratio_export %>%
  mutate(
    edu_combined = factor(edu_combined, 
                         levels = c("High School Graduate", 
                                   "Some College (No Degree)", 
                                   "Bachelor's")),
    predicted_values = dollar(predicted_values), 
    ratio = round(ratio, 2)
  ) %>%
  arrange(edu_combined, wordsum_percentile)

Supplementary: Predicted Lines by Age

# Build modelled career earnings trajectories for people of different education 
# levels and wordsum. Wordsum seems to have very little impact on earnings for 
# high school graduates.

if (inherits(model, "lm")) {
  predict_data <- expand_grid(
    age = seq(18, 65, by = 1),
    wordsum_percentile = c(24, 41, 73, 82),
    edu_combined = unique(gss1a_clean$edu_combined)
  )
  predictions <- predict_data %>% 
    mutate(
      predicted_income = predict(model, newdata = .),
      edu_combined = factor(edu_combined, 
                           levels = c("Less than High School",
                                     "High School Graduate", 
                                     "Some College (No Degree)",
                                     "Associate/Junior College",
                                     "Bachelor's",
                                     "Graduate Degree"))
    )
  
  ggplot(predictions, aes(x = age, y = predicted_income, color = factor(wordsum_percentile))) +
    geom_line() +
    facet_wrap(~edu_combined) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format()) +
    labs(title = "Predicted Income by Age, Wordsum Percentile, and Education Level",
                  x = "Age", y = "Predicted Income", color = "Wordsum Percentile") +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom")
}

Notes on Weights

Our descriptive statistics and regression models use GSS survey weights (wtssps) to make results representative of the US population. We do not take into account of the GSSâs possibly more complex survey design. This is likely fine for our purposes, but for rigorous inference, consult GSS documentation.
